      <h1>What are STIs?</h1>
      <p>Breaking down the facts about sexually transmitted infections: transmission, testing, treatment, and ending the stigma.</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>Understanding STIs</h2>
      <p>Sexually Transmitted Infections (STIs), formerly referred to as STDs (Sexually Transmitted Diseases), are infections that are passed from one person to another primarily through sexual contact. This includes vaginal, anal, and oral sex.</p>

      <p>It is important to understand that STIs are incredibly common. According to the CDC, there are millions of new infections every year. Anyone who is sexually active can get an STI, regardless of age, race, sexual orientation, or the number of partners they have had.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Bacterial vs. Viral STIs</h2>
      <p>STIs are generally caused by either bacteria or viruses, and this distinction is crucial because it determines how they are treated.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Bacterial STIs</h3>
        <p>These are caused by bacteria and are generally <strong>curable</strong> with a course of antibiotics. However, any damage done to the body before treatment may be permanent.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Chlamydia:</strong> The most commonly reported bacterial STI. Often asymptomatic, but can cause pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) if left untreated.</li>
          <li><strong>Gonorrhea:</strong> Similar to chlamydia, often asymptomatic, and can lead to serious complications if ignored.</li>
          <li><strong>Syphilis:</strong> Develops in stages, starting with a painless sore. Highly curable in early stages but can cause severe organ damage if untreated for years.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Viral STIs</h3>
        <p>These are caused by viruses. While they are <strong>not curable</strong>, they are highly <strong>manageable</strong> with medical treatment.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Human Papillomavirus (HPV):</strong> The most common STI. Many strains clear on their own, but some can cause genital warts or certain types of cancer (like cervical cancer). A highly effective vaccine is available.</li>
          <li><strong>Herpes (HSV):</strong> Causes painful blisters or sores. HSV-1 is usually oral (cold sores) and HSV-2 is usually genital, though both can appear in either location. Managed with antiviral medications.</li>
          <li><strong>HIV (Human Immunodeficiency Virus):</strong> Attacks the body's immune system. With modern antiretroviral therapy (ART), people with HIV can live long, healthy lives and reduce their viral load to undetectable levels, meaning they cannot transmit the virus to partners.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Importance of Testing</h2>
      <p>The most critical fact about STIs is that <strong>most people who have one do not show any symptoms.</strong> You can feel perfectly healthy, have no visible signs, and still pass an infection to a partner. The only way to know your status is to get tested.</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>When to test:</strong> At least annually if sexually active; more frequently (every 3-6 months) if you have multiple or new partners. Always test before stopping the use of barrier methods with a new partner.</li>
        <li><strong>What to ask for:</strong> A standard "STI panel" often only checks for chlamydia, gonorrhea, syphilis, and HIV. You usually have to specifically ask to be tested for herpes or trichomoniasis. There is currently no routine screening test for HPV in men.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Prevention and Protection</h2>
      <p>While the only 100% effective way to prevent STIs is abstinence, there are highly effective ways to reduce your risk:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Barrier Methods:</strong> Consistent and correct use of external condoms, internal condoms, and dental dams significantly reduces the risk of transmission for most STIs. Note that barrier methods do not offer complete protection against skin-to-skin STIs like herpes and HPV.</li>
        <li><strong>Vaccines:</strong> Get vaccinated against HPV and Hepatitis B.</li>
        <li><strong>PrEP (Pre-Exposure Prophylaxis):</strong> A daily pill (or periodic injection) that is highly effective at preventing HIV acquisition.</li>
        <li><strong>Communication:</strong> Talk openly with your partners about testing history and boundaries before engaging in sexual activity.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h3>Explore Related Topics</h3>
      <p>Understanding STIs is essential for informed consent and healthy relationships:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/sexual-health-glossary">The Complete Sexual Health Glossary</a> - Return to our main pillar page.</li>
        <li><a href="/what-is-consent">What is Consent?</a> - Learn why disclosing STI status is a crucial part of informed consent.</li>
        <li><a href="/what-is-pelvic-floor">What is the Pelvic Floor?</a> - Understand how chronic pelvic pain can sometimes be related to untreated infections.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-container">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h4>Can I have an STI without showing any symptoms?</h4>
          <p>Yes, absolutely. Many of the most common STIs, including chlamydia, gonorrhea, HPV, and herpes, are often completely asymptomatic. The only way to know your status for sure is to get tested.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h4>Are all STIs curable?</h4>
          <p>No. Bacterial STIs (like chlamydia, gonorrhea, and syphilis) are curable with antibiotics. Viral STIs (like HIV, herpes, and HPV) are not curable, but they are highly manageable with medical treatment.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h4>How often should I get tested for STIs?</h4>
          <p>If you are sexually active, it is generally recommended to get tested at least once a year. However, you should get tested more frequently (every 3-6 months) if you have multiple partners, a new partner, or if you don't consistently use barrier methods.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

